{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772563496,"nonce":"K7qo9GXPj3s4Ymfgf+1JYwXSShs=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87vgNj0","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/339","origin":"github"},"title":"ADR: Python package management policy (pip, venv, rosdep)","message":"## Summary\n\nWe need a clear policy on Python package management in this workspace. The current\nsituation has implicit rules that agents and contributors may not understand, leading\nto risky actions like running `pip install` on the system Python.\n\n## Context\n\n- **Ubuntu 24.04 / Python 3.12** enforces PEP 668 (`EXTERNALLY-MANAGED`), blocking\n  system-level `pip install` by default\n- **ROS 2 Jazzy** Python dependencies are managed through `rosdep`, which resolves\n  to system packages\n- The workspace has a **`.venv`** at the repo root, created during dev setup,\n  currently used for `pre-commit` and associated tools\n- AI agents working in the workspace need development tools (formatters, linters)\n  but have no documented guidance on where/how to install them\n- Two project repos have their own `.pre-commit-config.yaml` independent of the\n  workspace venv\n\n## Decision to Document\n\n### Build and Runtime Dependencies\n\nROS package build and runtime dependencies **must** be resolvable through `rosdep`.\nPackages must never require `pip install` as part of their build or runtime setup.\nThis ensures reproducibility and compatibility with the ROS dependency ecosystem.\n\n### Development Tools\n\nThe workspace `.venv` (created during dev setup) is the sanctioned location for\ndevelopment-only Python tools:\n\n- **Agents and contributors** may install dev tools into `.venv` (e.g., formatters,\n  linters, code generators)\n- The `.venv` must never be required for building or running ROS packages\n- The `.venv` is gitignored and workspace-local — project repos must not depend on it\n\n### Guardrails\n\n- **Never** run bare `pip install` (targets the system Python)\n- **Always** target `.venv` explicitly (`.venv/bin/pip install` or activate first)\n- Agents must verify they are targeting `.venv` before any pip operation\n\n### Pre-commit in Project Repos\n\nProject repos that include `.pre-commit-config.yaml` are responsible for documenting\ntheir own setup. The workspace `.venv` is a convenience, not a contract.\n\n### pipx\n\n`pipx` provides isolated installation of standalone CLI tools without affecting the\nsystem Python or the workspace `.venv`. It is a complementary option for tools that\nagents or contributors need ad-hoc, outside the managed venv. Consider adding `pipx`\nto workspace prerequisites.\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Should the ADR explicitly list which tools belong in `.venv` vs `pipx` vs apt?\n- Should agent instructions include a helper script/alias for safe pip operations?\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}